  "summary": "Pattern matches in bundled dev-tools CLI require human review",
  "details": "autotel-devtools ships minified/bundled CLI and server entry points (dist/cli.js, dist/index.js, dist/server/index.js, dist/widget.global.js) that contain keyword co-occurrences flagged by pattern rules: Buffer.from(..., 'base64').toString(...) decoding and proximity of 'ping' and 'POST' tokens. These patterns are common in legitimate dev-tooling bundles (telemetry pings, base64-encoded asset/config decoding, HTTP client helpers) and the keyword adjacency in single-line minified output is the weakest evidence shape. No traced execution path, no specific attacker-controlled destination, and no install-time lifecycle hook tying these to automatic execution on install were captured. Recommending human review to inspect the de-minified bundle and confirm whether the base64 decode and POST/ping calls correspond to documented telemetry/asset handling or to undeclared exfiltration.",
